##Harvard sends 'Eviction Letters' to students

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

Reporter, Nan Boyi, intern, Qu Sihan, thepaper.cn

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Over the past two days, more than 20,000 Harvard University students have been thrown off course by an email as they prepare for the weekend start of spring break.

In an e-mail on the morning of March 10 local time, Harvard's provost, Rakesh Khurana, asked all Harvard students to leave their dorms by 5 p.m. on March 15.

The e-mail was described by Jordan Patton, a 23-year-old undergraduate student, as an "eviction letter. ".

Harvard "closed school"

"I thought the worst thing would be to take more online classes, " Ivy, a Harvard Junior, told The Paper news www.thepaper.cn  . But now she has to move quickly from her dorm room to her home in the southern United States.

On March 4th the The Harvard Crimson, run by Harvard Students, reported that Claudine Gaye, Harvard's provost, was at a monthly faculty meeting, teachers are required to prepare for the possibility of using video software in the future. Just a week later, the situation had changed dramatically.

At 8:29 a.m. et on March 10, Harvard students received an email from president Laurence. In the email, Bakau told the students that Harvard had begun "transitioning to virtual education for graduate students and undergraduates in order to limit community members' exposure to the disease. ". The school's goal is to complete the transition by March 23, the first day Harvard students return to school after spring break.

Meanwhile, Harvard University requires that students who go home or on a trip during spring break do not return to campus after the break. Students who need to stay in school will also receive distance learning and "be prepared for severely restricted campus activities and interactions" . Bacall advised against non-essential activities for more than 25 people.

However, just 19 minutes later, at 8:48 p.m. , Harvard's provost, William Khurana, sent the e-mail asking all Harvard students to leave the university.

"when I saw the first email, I thought I was going to be quarantined in my dorm for Internet lessons. " Yixian, who had planned to return home for spring break, said she was "not going home. ". But after just over 10 minutes, her plan was broken by a second email.

International students and poor students face challenges

Like many Chinese students studying in the United States, Mike, who is from southern China, returned to China during her winter break at American universities. When he returned to Harvard at the end of January, the school was "unsupervised" and days later emailed to advise newly arrived students from China to "social distancing" others in their daily learning lives.

Mike felt that the American students around him were going on with their lives, treating the new pneumonia as if it were a common flu, and that even though studies have shown that all populations are susceptible, but "people in their 20s don't care. Their families care more. "

On February 1st the state of Massachusetts, home to Harvard University, confirmed its first case of pneumonia, but no new cases were reported for a month.

On March 6, however, three employees of Biogen, a Cambridge, massachusetts-based company, tested positive for the new coronavirus. The company held a Feb. 26 summit with 175 executives from around the world, according to The Boston Globe. On March 4, the company told the State's Public Health Department that two participants from Europe had tested positive for the new coronavirus upon their return. Of the 92 people who tested positive for proview, mass. , On March 6,70 were employees or close contacts of the company.

Cambridge, home to biogen, is also home to Harvard University and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.

Mike felt "understandable" about the "closure" that followed the outbreak. He cited Columbia University, also an Ivy League University, as an example, "If it's just a suspension, it's not going to protect students and faculty. Just as at Columbia, students still eat and party together on campus after the suspension was announced a few days ago, the virus spreads. For Harvard, it will be too late to have a confirmed case on campus. If all the students are segregated [ inside the school ] , the school can not support itself in terms of resources."

It's just that, Mike thinks, "the school is a little too tough on international students. " Though Harvard allows foreign students from countries currently on the CDC's level 3 alert until 9:00 a.m. local time on March 11, that is, the provost Khurana sent out an email within 24 hours to submit a detention application, "but there is no guarantee that it will be approved. ". "schools have also said they will subsidize travel for students from difficult families, but they will still need to approve travel, " Mike added.

"We know it will be a challenge for some of you to leave campus in a short time, " Khurana wrote in an email to students.

International students are not the only ones facing challenges.

In the space of three days, Yixian had to find a way to empty the room of her own things, as for the plants in her dormitory, she did not know what to do with them.

To make matters worse, many Harvard students from low-income families in the United States rely on the The Harvard Crimson for "food, housing and stability. ". For the first generation of college students from low-income families, the "minimum notice" has caused great distress in their lives. Eric Olvera, a freshman, told the paper that he had spent $700 on a plane ticket home, "which is half my fortune" .

Mike bought a flight home as soon as he was told. "I woke up in an online school and hoped the epidemic would get better soon, " he wrote in a group of friends. Some senior students brought champagne to campus and took "graduation photos" ahead of time, in case I don't make it back to campus in the spring before graduation.

At 13:43 eastern time on March 11, students at Harvard received a new email from the university's Health Services, saying that two Harvard students were being tested for the new coronavirus.
